  <!-- Section 1: What is an FHA loan? -->
  <h2 id="what-is-an-fha-loan">What Is an FHA Loan?</h2>
  <p>
    An FHA loan is a mortgage insured by the Federal Housing Administration, a division of the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD). The government does not lend you money directly. Instead, it insures the loan so that private lenders — banks, credit unions, and mortgage companies — can offer you more flexible terms than they otherwise would.
  </p>
  <p>
    That government backing is what makes FHA loans so popular with first-time buyers. Lenders know the FHA will cover part of their loss if a borrower defaults, which means they can accept lower credit scores, smaller down payments, and higher debt-to-income ratios than conventional loan guidelines typically allow.
  </p>
  <p>
    FHA loans are not limited to first-time buyers. Anyone who meets the requirements can apply. However, the program's low down payment option and flexible underwriting make it especially attractive if you are purchasing your first home in an expensive market like San Diego.
  </p>

  <!-- Section 2: Who qualifies? -->
  <h2 id="who-qualifies">Who Qualifies for an FHA Loan?</h2>
  <p>
    FHA eligibility is based on a few key factors. You do not need to be a first-time homebuyer, but the property must be your primary residence — FHA loans cannot be used for investment properties or vacation homes.
  </p>
  <h3>Credit Score</h3>
  <p>
    The FHA sets a floor of 500, but your required score depends on your down payment. With a score of 580 or higher, you qualify for the minimum 3.5% down payment. Scores between 500 and 579 require a 10% down payment. Most San Diego lenders prefer to work with borrowers who have at least a 580 score, and some set their own minimum at 620.
  </p>
  <h3>Debt-to-Income Ratio</h3>
  <p>
    FHA guidelines allow a front-end ratio (housing costs only) of up to 31% and a back-end ratio (all monthly debt payments) of up to 43%. With strong compensating factors — such as cash reserves or a long employment history — some lenders will approve ratios up to 50%.
  </p>
  <h3>Employment and Income</h3>
  <p>
    You will need to document steady employment, typically at least two years of work history in the same field. Self-employed borrowers can qualify with two years of tax returns showing consistent income. There is no minimum income requirement, but your income must be enough to support the monthly payment.
  </p>
  <h3>Property Requirements</h3>
  <p>
    The home must meet FHA minimum property standards, which means it needs to be safe, structurally sound, and habitable. An FHA-approved appraiser will inspect the property. Condominiums must be in an FHA-approved complex, which can narrow your options in certain San Diego neighborhoods.
  </p>

  <!-- Section 3: FHA loan limits in San Diego -->
  <h2 id="fha-loan-limits-san-diego">FHA Loan Limits in San Diego</h2>
  <p>
    San Diego County is classified as a high-cost area, which means FHA loan limits here are significantly higher than the national floor. For 2026, the single-family FHA loan limit in San Diego County is <strong>$1,077,550</strong>.
  </p>
  <p>
    That limit covers a large portion of the local housing market. According to recent data, the median home price in San Diego County hovers around $900,000, which means most entry-level and mid-range homes fall within FHA guidelines.
  </p>
  <ComparisonTable
    headers={["Property Type", "2026 FHA Limit (San Diego County)"]}
    rows={[
      ["Single-family", "$1,077,550"],
      ["Duplex", "$1,378,850"],
      ["Triplex", "$1,666,500"],
      ["Four-plex", "$2,071,600"],
    ]}
    caption="2026 FHA loan limits for San Diego County (estimates only)"
  />
  <p>
    These limits are reviewed and updated annually based on local home prices. If you are shopping for a home above the single-family limit, you would need to consider a conventional jumbo loan instead.
  </p>

  <!-- Section 4: Down payment requirements -->
  <h2 id="down-payment-requirements">Down Payment Requirements</h2>
  <p>
    One of the biggest advantages of an FHA loan is the low down payment. Here is how it breaks down:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>3.5% down</strong> with a credit score of 580 or higher</li>
    <li><strong>10% down</strong> with a credit score between 500 and 579</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    On a $700,000 home in San Diego, a 3.5% down payment comes to $24,500. Compare that to 20% down on a conventional loan, which would be $140,000 — a difference that can take years to save.
  </p>
  <p>
    Your down payment can come from several sources, including personal savings, gift funds from a family member, employer-assisted housing programs, or down payment assistance grants. San Diego has multiple DPA programs specifically designed to layer on top of FHA loans (more on that below).
  </p>
  <p>
    Keep in mind that a smaller down payment means you start with less equity in the home and will pay mortgage insurance for the life of the loan (unless you refinance later into a conventional mortgage).
  </p>

  <!-- Section 5: Pros and cons -->
  <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Pros and Cons of FHA Loans</h2>
  <ComparisonTable
    headers={["Pros", "Cons"]}
    rows={[
      ["Low 3.5% down payment", "Mortgage insurance premium (MIP) required for life of loan"],
      ["Credit scores as low as 500 accepted", "FHA appraisal standards can be stricter than conventional"],
      ["Higher debt-to-income ratios allowed (up to 50% with compensating factors)", "Loan limits may not cover luxury or high-end homes"],
      ["Gift funds allowed for entire down payment", "Condos must be in FHA-approved complexes"],
      ["Competitive interest rates", "Cannot be used for investment properties"],
      ["Compatible with most San Diego DPA programs", "Upfront MIP of 1.75% added to loan balance"],
    ]}
    caption="FHA loan advantages and disadvantages"
  />

  <!-- Section 6: FHA vs other loan types -->
  <h2 id="fha-vs-other-loans">FHA vs. Conventional vs. VA Loans</h2>
  <p>
    Choosing between loan types depends on your credit profile, military service history, and how much you have saved. Here is a side-by-side comparison:
  </p>
  <ComparisonTable
    headers={["Feature", "FHA", "Conventional", "VA"]}
    rows={[
      ["Min. down payment", "3.5%", "3% (Conventional 97)", "0%"],
      ["Min. credit score", "580 (3.5% down)", "620+", "No VA minimum"],
      ["Mortgage insurance", "MIP for life of loan", "PMI until 20% equity", "None (funding fee instead)"],
      ["Loan limit (SD)", "$1,077,550", "$766,550 (conforming)", "No limit with full entitlement"],
      ["Property types", "Primary residence only", "Primary, second home, investment", "Primary residence only"],
      ["Who can apply", "Any qualified borrower", "Any qualified borrower", "Veterans, active duty, eligible spouses"],
      ["Best for", "Lower credit, small savings", "Strong credit, PMI avoidance", "Military-connected buyers"],
    ]}
    caption="Loan type comparison for San Diego homebuyers (estimates only)"
    highlightColumn={1}
  />
  <p>
    If you are a veteran or active-duty service member, a VA loan will almost always save you more money. If you have strong credit and 20% saved, a conventional loan avoids mortgage insurance entirely. For buyers with modest credit and limited savings, FHA is often the most accessible path to homeownership in San Diego.
  </p>

  <!-- Section 7: How to apply -->
  <h2 id="how-to-apply">How to Apply for an FHA Loan in San Diego</h2>
  <p>
    The FHA loan process is similar to any other mortgage application, with a few extra steps. Here is what to expect:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Check your credit.</strong> Pull your free annual credit report from AnnualCreditReport.com and review it for errors. If your score is below 580, you may want to spend a few months improving it before applying.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Gather your documents.</strong> You will need recent pay stubs, W-2s or tax returns from the past two years, bank statements, and identification. Self-employed borrowers should also prepare a year-to-date profit-and-loss statement.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Get pre-approved.</strong> A pre-approval letter tells sellers you are a serious buyer and gives you a clear price range. In San Diego's competitive market, many sellers will not consider offers without one.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Find an FHA-approved lender.</strong> Not every lender offers FHA loans, and among those that do, rates and fees vary. Compare at least three lenders to find the best combination of rate, closing costs, and service.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Shop for your home.</strong> Work with a real estate agent who knows the San Diego market. If you are looking at condos, confirm the complex is on the FHA-approved list before making an offer.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Complete the FHA appraisal.</strong> Your lender will order an appraisal from an FHA-approved appraiser. The appraiser checks both the market value and whether the property meets FHA minimum standards.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Close on your loan.</strong> Once underwriting is complete and all conditions are cleared, you sign your closing documents, fund the loan, and receive your keys.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    The entire process typically takes 30 to 45 days from pre-approval to closing, though timelines can vary depending on the lender and the complexity of your application.
  </p>

  <!-- Section 8: DPA programs that work with FHA -->
  <h2 id="dpa-programs">Down Payment Assistance Programs That Work with FHA Loans</h2>
  <p>
    One of the biggest advantages of choosing an FHA loan in San Diego is that it is compatible with nearly every local and state down payment assistance program. Here are the main ones:
  </p>
  <h3>San Diego Housing Commission (SDHC)</h3>
  <p>
    SDHC offers deferred-payment loans for down payment and closing cost assistance to first-time buyers purchasing within the City of San Diego. The amount varies by program and income level. These funds can be layered on top of an FHA first mortgage, reducing or eliminating the cash you need to bring to closing.
  </p>
  <h3>CalHFA MyHome Assistance Program</h3>
  <p>
    MyHome provides a deferred-payment junior loan of up to 3.5% of the purchase price (or appraised value, whichever is less) that can be applied directly to your FHA down payment. The loan has no monthly payments and is repaid when you sell, refinance, or pay off the first mortgage.
  </p>
  <h3>GSFA Platinum Program</h3>
  <p>
    The Golden State Finance Authority offers down payment assistance of up to 5.5% of the loan amount. GSFA assistance can be structured as a gift (no repayment required) or a repayable second loan, depending on the program tier. It pairs well with FHA first mortgages and is available statewide.
  </p>
  <h3>CalHFA Dream For All</h3>
  <p>
    When funded, Dream For All provides a shared appreciation loan of up to 20% of the purchase price (capped at $150,000) for first-time buyers. This program has limited funding rounds and is highly competitive, but it can dramatically reduce your upfront costs when combined with an FHA loan.
  </p>
  <p>
    Each program has its own income limits, purchase price caps, and application deadlines. A local lender who works with these programs regularly can help you determine which combinations you qualify for.
  </p>

